Level-0 Motion: There is no god, Side: for
    Level-1 Data : {"claim": "Lack of compelling evidence supports the non-existence of God.", "argument": ["Absence of evidence suggests the simplest explanation is the non-existence of God.", "The principle of parsimony (Occam's Razor) favors the explanation requiring the fewest assumptions."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The opponent bears the burden of proof due to their strong atheist stance.", "argument": ["Strong atheism requires demonstrating God's non-existence, not just lacking belief.", "Asserting non-existence based solely on lack of proof for existence is a logical fallacy (argument from ignorance)."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "The opponent commits a straw man fallacy by misrepresenting my position.", "argument": ["The opponent is misrepresenting my position.", "My position is that I see no compelling reason to believe in a god and therefore conclude there likely isn\u2019t one, not that I am definitively proving non-existence."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Agnosticism acknowledges the impossibility of definitively disproving God's existence.", "argument": ["It is impossible to definitively disprove the existence of God."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The Kalam cosmological argument supports the possibility of God's existence.", "argument": ["Everything that begins to exist has a cause.", "The universe began to exist (Big Bang theory, Borde-Guth-Vilenkin theorem).", "Therefore, the universe has a cause, which can be called God."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "The Kalam Cosmological Argument only points to an uncaused cause, not necessarily God.", "argument": ["The argument makes a leap in logic by equating an uncaused cause with the specific God my opponent is arguing for.", "It commits a non sequitur fallacy."]}
                Level-4 Data : {"claim": "The proposition mischaracterizes the Kalam cosmological argument and the concept of the uncaused cause.", "argument": ["The Kalam cosmological argument and the concept of the uncaused cause are misrepresented.", "The uncaused cause provides a foundation for God as a timeless, spaceless entity.", "A timeless, spaceless entity is not subject to physical laws."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "Arguing that the universe must have a cause because everything in it does is a fallacy of composition.", "argument": ["The opponent is assuming that what is true of the parts (things in the universe) is also true of the whole (the universe itself).", "The opponent hasn't proven that the universe requires a cause."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The opponent's argument misrepresents the theistic position by claiming a God bound by spacetime could not have created the universe.", "argument": ["This is a straw man argument.", "It ignores conceptions of God as existing *outside* of spacetime, unbound by physical laws.", "It presumes knowledge of pre-Big Bang conditions that current physics simply doesn't possess."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The opponent's argument that scientific explanations replace \"God of the gaps\" arguments rendering God useless is flawed.", "argument": ["Even if some gaps have been filled, this doesn't negate the possibility of a creator God.", "The creation of the universe itself, if true, is hardly \"nothing.\"", "Many find God to be a source of hope, morality, and central to their lives.", "This perceived utility, combined with potential roles in areas like guided evolution or miracles, renders the \"uselessness\" claim baseless.", "Replacing *some* explanations doesn't invalidate *all* similar explanations."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The opponent's arguments fail to refute the existence of an omnipotent creator God.", "argument": ["The first argument only addresses a time-bound God.", "The second argument is a non-sequitur, failing to address either a time-bound or eternal God."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "The opponent misrepresented and misapplied the Kalam Cosmological Argument.", "argument": ["The Kalam Cosmological Argument only argues for an uncaused cause, not necessarily God.", "Equating an uncaused cause with the God of classical theism is a non sequitur fallacy.", "The opponent failed to provide justification for equating an uncaused cause with God."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The proposition misunderstands the nature of physical laws and their relation to metaphysical entities.", "argument": ["Physical laws describe how the universe works, not necessarily why.", "Physical laws are subject to revision.", "Physical laws describe natural phenomena, not metaphysical entities.", "A timeless, non-physical God is not bound by physical laws."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The proposition misrepresents the concept of falsifiability and commits an argument from ignorance.", "argument": ["Inability to definitively prove or disprove something doesn't render it false.", "Lack of definitive proof for or against God doesn't equate to non-existence.", "Dismissing a concept due to lack of proof is an argument from ignorance."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The proposition's argument incorrectly limits an omnipotent being to physical possibility, rather than logical possibility.", "argument": ["An omnipotent being is bound by logical possibility, not physical limitations.", "An omnipotent being could operate outside of physical laws."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The proposition has failed to meet its burden of proof to demonstrate the non-existence of God.", "argument": ["The proposition bears the burden of proof to demonstrate the non-existence of God.", "The proposition relies on a misunderstanding of physical laws and misrepresents logical arguments.", "Dismissing the uncaused cause due to lack of proof is an argument from ignorance.", "The proposition's arguments are insufficient to disprove the existence of God."]}
    Level-1 Data : {"claim": "The side of non-belief is open to changing its position if credible evidence emerges.", "argument": ["The position is not dogmatic but open to revision based on new evidence.", "Acknowledges the possibility of future evidence supporting the existence of God."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "The opponent misrepresents my position and commits the fallacy of burden shifting.", "argument": ["The burden of proof rests on the opponent to prove the non-existence of God, not on me to prove God's existence."]}
    Level-1 Data : {"claim": "The opposition is asked to specify which god they believe in and provide evidence for that specific deity.", "argument": ["Challenges the opposition to define their concept of God.", "Demands specific evidence for the existence of the proposed deity."]}

Level-0 Motion: Morality Is Objective, Side: for
    Level-1 Data : {"claim": "Morality is objective, stemming from our evolutionary biology.", "argument": ["Biological cues dictate our sense of right and wrong.", "Underlying cues are objective, biological facts.", "Morality is concerned with group and individual well-being.", "Humans are social animals.", "Evolutionary cues promote group survival.", "Personal interpretations of morality can be subjective.", "Underlying evolutionary cues are objective and exist independently of opinions.", "Evolution explains widespread agreement on core moral principles.", "Evolution explains deviations through individual interpretation and cultural variation.", "Evolution explains the 'why' behind moral decision-making.", "Evolution provides a coherent model explaining shared moral foundations and individual differences.", "Evolution is a more robust and complete explanation than alternatives."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Morality is a social construct built upon evolving human feelings and societal norms, not a universal truth.", "argument": ["Morality is not derived from some external, universal truth.", "Morality is a social construct.", "This construct is built upon evolving human feelings and societal norms.", "Morality depends heavily on societal context.", "Morality arises from the complex interaction of our brains within a specific cultural context.", "Morality is a social construct.", "Morality is not an objective feature of the universe.", "Our capacity for moral reasoning might have evolutionary roots.", "The content of our morality remains a product of social construction.", "Morality is not objective reality."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "The expression of morality (moral codes) is distinct from its origin (biological cues).", "argument": ["Moral codes vary across societies.", "The capacity for moral judgment stems from objective biological cues related to harm and well-being."]}
            Level-3 Data : {"claim": "The source of morality (evolutionary cues) is distinct from individual moral judgments.", "argument": ["Evolutionary cues promote group survival.", "Personal interpretations of morality can be subjective.", "Underlying evolutionary cues are objective and exist independently of opinions."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Morality cannot be objectively defined.", "argument": ["Morality is subjective.", "Therefore, morality cannot be objectively defined."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Morality is distinct from compassion and ethics, and can even contradict them.", "argument": ["Compassion, while potentially biological, doesn't define morality.", "Ethics and morality are distinct concepts.", "Morality can contradict both compassion and ethics, as shown by historical and cultural examples."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Objectivity of existence does not equate to objectivity of interpretation, leading to diverse moral systems.", "argument": ["Different interpretations of biological cues lead to diverse moral systems.", "The existence of the debate itself highlights the subjectivity of morality."]}
        Level-2 Data : {"claim": "Evolutionary advantage does not equate to objective moral good.", "argument": ["Immoral actions can lead to individual success.", "Evolutionary advantage does not equate to objective moral good."]}
